apt remove
  
RHEL/CentOS:
yum install
dnf install

9. Disk & File System

df -h      # Shows disk space usage of all mounted filesystems in human-readable format (GB/MB)
du -sh     # Shows total size of a directory in human-readable format
mount      # Displays all mounted filesystems OR mounts a filesystem
umount     # Unmounts (detaches) a filesystem from the directory structure
lsblk      # Lists all block devices (disks, partitions, volumes) in a tree format
blkid      # Shows UUID and filesystem type of disks/partitions

df -h → How much disk is used?
du -sh → Which folder is using space?
lsblk → What disks are attached?
mount/umount → Attach/detach storage
blkid → Identify disks (UUID, type)

10. Logs

tail -f /var/log/syslog        # View system logs in real-time (live monitoring)
tail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log   # Monitor incoming HTTP requests to Nginx in real-time
journalctl                    # View logs managed by systemd (all services)
journalctl -u nginx           # View logs of a specific service (nginx)

11. User Management

whoami     # Shows current logged-in user
id         # Shows user ID (UID), group ID (GID), and groups
useradd    # Creates a new user
usermod    # Modifies user (add to group, change shell, etc.)
passwd     # Sets or changes user password
groups     # Shows groups a user belongs to

whoami → Who am I logged in as?
id → Check permissions & group access
useradd → Create new user
usermod → Manage user roles/access
passwd → Set/reset password
groups → Check user permissions via groups

12. Compression & Archiving

tar -cvf file.tar dir/    # Create archive (combine files)
tar -xvf file.tar         # Extract archive
gzip file                 # Compress file (.gz)
gunzip file.gz            # Decompress file
zip file.zip file1        # Create zip archive
unzip file.zip            # Extract zip file

tar → Archive files/folders (backup, transfer)
gzip → Compress files (reduce size)
zip/unzip → Common format for sharing files

13. Docker + System

docker ps                 # List running containers
docker logs <container>   # View container logs
docker exec -it <container> bash   # Access running container (interactive shell)
docker inspect <container>         # Detailed info (IP, config, metadata)

docker ps → Which containers are running?
docker logs → Debug container issues
docker exec → Go inside container
docker inspect → Deep troubleshooting (network, volumes, etc.)


|| DevOps Command Combos ||

1. Check logs in real-time  :  tail -f /var/log/app.log | grep ERROR

2. Find large files  :  du -ah / | sort -rh | head -10 
  du-ah displays the disk usage of all files and directories (including hidden ones) in a human-readable format (e.g., KB, MB, GB).

3. Find process using port : lsof -i :8080

4. Kill process by name  :   pkill nginx
